reut2-008.sgm, YUGOSLAVIA CHANGES CONTROVERSIAL WAGE-FREEZE LAW, The Yugoslav government has decided toamend a wage-freeze law that triggered nationwide strikes andled the Prime Minister to threaten to use troops if the unrestthreatened the ruling Communist Party.    The law, which returned wages to the average levels of thelast quarter of 1986, triggered a huge wave of strikes andlabor unrest throughout Yugoslavia and a chorus of disapprovalfrom company bosses and union officials. Some 70 strikes bythousands of workers erupted nationwide.    The official Tanjug news agency reported last night thegovernment said the law, initially covering all firms in thecountry, would be amended for seasonal industries and forcompanies which raised wages rationally" last year. It did notsay what the amendments would be. Reuter&#3;

