reut2-008.sgm, E-TRON CORP REACHES AGREEMENT WITH FORMER PRES, E-tron Corp said it will submit asettlement agreement reached with its former president to thebankruptcy court for approval.    It said the settlement stems from a suit against the formercompany president.    E-tron, which is in Chapter 11, said the settlement callsfor Irwin Lampert to return 2,350,000 shares of E-tron stock toits treasury, and prohibits Lampert from starting a businesscompetive with E-tron, the company said.    It added Irwin must repay certain debts, also.    E-tron said it will submit soon a creditor proposal plan toget out of Chapter 11. Reuter&#3;
reut2-008.sgm, SALOMON OFFERS UNITS OF VAN DUSEN AIRPORT L.P., Salomon Brothers Inc, acting as soleunderwriter, said it is publicly offering 50,000 units of VanDusen Airport Services Co, L.P.    The offering consists of 50 mln dlrs of 12 pct seniorsubordinated notes due 1997 and 50,000 contingent paymentobligations. The notes are priced at par, or 1,000 dlrs each.    A unit has one par value note and one contingent paymentobligation. The notes are redeemable by Van Dusen after March15, 1992, Salomon said.    A payment obligation entitles the holder to receive a cashpayment under certain events, or to certain repurchase rights. Reuter&#3;
reut2-008.sgm, BERLINER BANK OUTLINES LOSSES, &lt;Berliner Bank AG> has sufferedlosses of between 25 mln and 30 mln marks on credits extendedby its Stuttgart branch by bank officials who exceeded theirpowers, a bank spokesman said.    The spokesman, replying to queries about press reports,said he could not rule out the possibility that the final lossfigure may be slightly above this range.    Late last week the bank said only that the losses from thecredits in Stuttgart would be in the double-digit millions." Reuter&#3;

